special correspondent Nadja

25:00.700 --> 25:03.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Drost and videographer
Bruno Federico report.

25:03.100 --> 25:07.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And a warning: Images and
accounts in this story
may upset some viewers.

25:07.666 --> 25:12.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NADJA DROST: An hour outside
of the capital, Caracas, traces
of a once-productive industrial

25:14.700 --> 25:19.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and agricultural region flank
the highway outside the town
of Yare, an abandoned factory,

25:21.600 --> 25:26.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a farm, deserted and
overgrown, the carcass of
a government dairy project.

25:28.666 --> 25:33.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
These buildings, like the
economy they once helped
support, are in collapse.

25:33.500 --> 25:38.500 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Katiuska Morales' husband
can only find occasional
work as a day laborer,
and the family faces

25:40.733 --> 25:45.066 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
nationwide shortages of food
at runaway inflation prices.

25:45.066 --> 25:50.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KATIUSKA MORALES, Venezuela
(through translator):
Everything is expensive.

25:52.033 --> 25:55.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What one earns in three or four
days of work is what it costs
to buy one kilogram of rice.

25:56.900 --> 25:59.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
NADJA DROST: Morales
can't feed her family.

25:59.233 --> 26:04.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KATIUSKA MORALES (through
translator): When the boy says,
mama, I want food, I can't find

26:05.400 --> 26:07.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the way to tell
him there is none.

26:07.500 --> 26:11.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NADJA DROST: The only thing in
the family's kitchen today are
mangoes, stored in the oven

26:13.266 --> 26:16.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
under the attentive eye of
3-year-old David, who searches
amongst the bruised fruit for

26:16.200 --> 26:18.833 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a good one.

26:18.833 --> 26:23.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
With its economy in freefall,
and food prices skyrocketing,
many Venezuelans are eating

26:24.566 --> 26:26.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
less and less every day.

26:26.700 --> 26:31.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One recent study found that,
in the last year, 75 percent
of Venezuelans lost an average

26:32.300 --> 26:34.400 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of 19 pounds.

26:34.400 --> 26:39.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But it is children who
are suffering the most,
and severe malnutrition
among them is rising

26:40.033 --> 26:42.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
at an alarming rate.

26:42.833 --> 26:47.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Three out of Morales' six
children have been diagnosed
with severe malnutrition.

26:47.733 --> 26:49.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
She's most worried about
her 10-month old baby.

26:49.733 --> 26:52.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
KATIUSKA MORALES (through
translator): I see her small.

26:52.000 --> 26:53.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
She doesn't grow.

26:53.200 --> 26:55.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
She doesn't try
crawling or walking.

26:55.100 --> 26:58.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I feel I have to be careful that
she doesn't fall to the side.

26:58.533 --> 27:00.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's like she's faint.

27:00.633 --> 27:04.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NADJA DROST: Back in Caracas,
Susana Raffalli, who specializes
in food emergencies for the

27:06.633 --> 27:10.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Catholic charity Caritas,
has carried out a
study on malnutrition.

27:10.333 --> 27:14.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
SUSANA RAFFALLI, Caritas
(through translator):
We have gone from having
8 percent of children

27:14.933 --> 27:19.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with severe malnutrition
in October, to 12 percent
in just four months.

27:19.666 --> 27:23.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When a child loses 30 to 40
percent of their weight, that's
called severe malnutrition.

27:23.866 --> 27:28.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Why is that severe?

27:28.100 --> 27:32.566 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Because the child is so
skinny, it is at risk of dying.

27:32.566 --> 27:37.566 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NADJA DROST: In a country
sitting on the biggest
oil reserves in the
world, why has it become

27:39.100 --> 27:43.066 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
so difficult for so many to eat?

27:43.066 --> 27:48.066 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Almost entirely reliant
on oil exports, Venezuela
barely produces anything
of its own, and has

27:48.966 --> 27:51.700 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
relied hugely on food imports.

27:51.700 --> 27:56.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But with oil revenues down,
corruption and an economy in
shambles, the government hardly

27:57.900 --> 27:59.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
has any dollars to
sell to importers.

27:59.933 --> 28:04.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SUSANA RAFFALLI (through
translator): There is at least
a 30 to 40 percent shortage in

28:04.266 --> 28:08.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the availability of food,
because it's not being produced,
nor is it getting imported.

28:08.633 --> 28:10.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We don't know how this
void will get filled.

28:10.666 --> 28:15.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NADJA DROST: To alleviate
the scarcity, the government
recently decided to loosen its

28:15.200 --> 28:20.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
monopoly on many food imports
to allow other importers
to bring in staples.

28:22.700 --> 28:25.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Some shortages have eased,
but now, with triple-digit
inflation driving up
prices, few can afford

28:27.200 --> 28:31.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to pay for even the
most basic goods.

28:31.066 --> 28:36.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We're on our way to one of the
biggest hospitals in Caracas
to visit the pediatric unit.

28:38.066 --> 28:41.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But four years ago, when the
crisis started deepening, the
government banned the use of

28:42.566 --> 28:44.700 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
any cameras inside hospitals.

28:44.700 --> 28:48.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Because of that, and the fact
that the hospital and the area
around it is full of military

28:50.433 --> 28:53.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and government=aligned militia,
we're going to have to try
to enter unnoticed, and with

28:54.500 --> 28:56.900 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a hidden camera.

28:56.900 --> 29:01.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Once inside, we follow Dr. Livia
Machado, an expert in child
nutrition, into the emergency

29:02.633 --> 29:03.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ward for children.

29:03.766 --> 29:05.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
This baby's diagnosis?

29:05.366 --> 29:07.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Malnutrition, at
seven months old.

29:07.166 --> 29:09.266 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

29:09.266 --> 29:10.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LIVIA MACHADO, Child Nutrition
Expert (through translator): She
was born six-and-a-half pounds.

29:10.233 --> 29:12.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Now she weighs seven.

29:12.300 --> 29:15.300 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The economic conditions now
don't allow her to buy formula.

29:15.300 --> 29:19.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WOMAN (through translator):
It became more expensive,
and I couldn't afford it.

29:19.500 --> 29:21.466 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

29:21.466 --> 29:24.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LIVIA MACHADO (through
translator): The most important
thing is that there's no access

29:24.300 --> 29:25.766 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to baby formula.

29:25.766 --> 29:27.266 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You can't get it in the country.

29:27.266 --> 29:30.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And when you can, it's
at such high prices.

29:30.866 --> 29:33.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
How much did you pay the
last time for formula?

29:33.066 --> 29:35.533 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
WOMAN: Twenty thousand bolivars.

29:35.533 --> 29:40.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NADJA DROST: That's a third
of a month's minimum wage for
three days' worth of formula.

29:43.233 --> 29:46.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Five of the 20 children in this
unit have severe malnutrition.

29:46.800 --> 29:51.166 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Dr. Machado worries about the
increase in cases she sees.

29:51.166 --> 29:53.333 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

29:53.333 --> 29:55.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
LIVIA MACHADO (through
translator): But even
more worrisome, and
something I have never

29:55.833 --> 30:00.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
seen and that strikes me as
critical, are children who
are between half-a-year and a

30:02.700 --> 30:05.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
year-old and they have
never even gained two
pounds in their whole life.

30:05.633 --> 30:06.933 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
NADJA DROST: Like this baby.

30:06.933 --> 30:09.566 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

30:09.566 --> 30:12.933 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LIVIA MACHADO (through
translator): Her condition
is very critical, from a
respiratory and metabolic

30:14.333 --> 30:17.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
perspective, and everything
that triggered this was hunger.

30:17.333 --> 30:22.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
NADJA DROST: I ask how
many months old she is.

30:22.233 --> 30:23.933 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

30:23.933 --> 30:25.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
LIVIA MACHADO (through
translator): Eleven
months, almost a year.

30:25.333 --> 30:27.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And she doesn't even
weigh nine pounds.

30:27.733 --> 30:32.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NADJA DROST: Dr. Machado says
this baby's mother hardly
eats anything herself in order

30:34.066 --> 30:37.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to give what she can
to her six children.

30:37.166 --> 30:41.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But it's been woefully
inadequate, and brought the
baby to a critical state.

30:41.733 --> 30:46.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The child has suffered
two cardiac arrests here.

30:47.500 --> 30:50.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
She died the next day.

30:50.966 --> 30:55.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
But it's not just the
deadly malnutrition.

30:55.033 --> 31:00.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There is little medication to
treat the many complications
that it can cause.

31:01.733 --> 31:05.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Hospitals have less
than 5 percent of the
medications they need.

31:07.800 --> 31:10.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the desperation of doctors
and nurses trying to work with
broken equipment and without

31:12.733 --> 31:16.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
lifesaving treatments
is driving them into
the streets to protest.

31:16.500 --> 31:19.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What do they want?

31:19.966 --> 31:24.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WOMAN (through translator):
Supplies for hospitals,
food, medicine, to be able
to attend to patients.

31:27.866 --> 31:32.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
NADJA DROST: The flow
of medicines into the
country has plummeted
after most foreign drug

31:34.666 --> 31:38.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
companies cut off ties
with Venezuela over $6
billion-plus in unpaid debts.

31:40.066 --> 31:44.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
To ease the shortage, these
doctors and nurses are demanding
that the government open what

31:44.266 --> 31:49.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they call a humanitarian
channel to allow for
donations of medications.

31:51.733 --> 31:54.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The government has said
that accepting humanitarian
relief would expose Venezuela
to foreign intervention.

31:56.366 --> 32:01.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But some organizations are
finding ways around what they
say amounts to a government ban

32:01.600 --> 32:04.300 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
on aid.

32:04.300 --> 32:08.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Accion Solidaria is part
of a coalition promoting
health rights, Codevida.

32:08.600 --> 32:13.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Its president, Francisco
Valencia, leads us to a storage
room that's been converted to

32:15.533 --> 32:18.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
what looks like a well-organized
ad hoc pharmacy that accepts
donations of medications and

32:20.233 --> 32:22.733 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
distributes them to Venezuelans.

32:22.733 --> 32:27.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRANCISCO VALENCIA, Codevida
(through translator): Here,
all of these medications
come from abroad.

32:29.000 --> 32:31.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Because of the situation
here, you can't get
these medications here.

32:31.833 --> 32:34.600 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Here, we have
painkillers, antibiotics.

32:34.600 --> 32:37.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
There's medicine for
children as well.

32:37.166 --> 32:42.100 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NADJA DROST: The supplies
are sent by Venezuelans
and other donors from
around the world, but

32:44.000 --> 32:47.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in small packages, to
avoid suspicion and bypass
customs authorities.

32:47.233 --> 32:51.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
FRANCISCO VALENCIA
(through translator):
Door-to-door deliveries.

32:51.233 --> 32:52.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They're sent privately.

32:52.533 --> 32:55.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
NADJA DROST: Like
a courier company.

32:55.966 --> 33:00.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Once Valencia and his colleagues
categorize the new shipments,
they announce their stockpile

33:00.700 --> 33:03.700 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
over Twitter, Facebook and
on local radio stations.

33:03.700 --> 33:08.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Their hot line number is flooded
with calls from Venezuelans
wanting to claim the medicines

33:08.333 --> 33:12.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FRANCISCO VALENCIA (through
translator): So far, we have
been able to give medication

33:12.400 --> 33:14.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to over 5,000 people.

33:14.400 --> 33:18.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NADJA DROST: But Valencia knows
that what they provide is a
mere drop in a sea of need.

33:20.666 --> 33:22.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FRANCISCO VALENCIA (through
translator): If you see this
here, it's not a quantity to

33:22.266 --> 33:24.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
supply all of Venezuela.

33:24.300 --> 33:28.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NADJA DROST: Valencia and
others in health organizations
say the government needs to

33:28.200 --> 33:33.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
recognize that Venezuela
is facing a humanitarian
crisis, and one that
warrants government and

33:34.733 --> 33:36.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
international action.

33:36.766 --> 33:41.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SUSANA RAFFALLI (through
translator): What we're asking
is that they do something and

33:43.300 --> 33:45.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
make available the resources
that are needed here, because
it's not just Caritas that is

33:45.600 --> 33:47.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
sounding the alarm
of what will happen.

33:47.833 --> 33:49.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It is happening to us.

33:49.566 --> 33:52.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And there are children with
malnutrition dying in hospitals.

33:52.333 --> 33:57.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NADJA DROST: For the
"PBS NewsHour," reporting
with Bruno Federico, I'm
Nadja Drost in Caracas.

34:03.800 --> 34:08.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Next: You
need some cash real quick?

34:12.900 --> 34:16.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Economics correspondent Paul
Solman explores why, for some
customers, the best bet might

34:16.400 --> 34:18.300 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
not be the bank.

34:18.300 --> 34:20.833 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's part of his weekly series
Making Sense of financial news.

34:20.833 --> 34:25.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JOE COLEMAN, President,
RiteCheck: And this
is East 138th Street,
which in many ways is

34:25.033 --> 34:27.033 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the Wall Street of the Bronx.

34:27.033 --> 34:30.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You have got a lot of
financial service providers
along the street, bodegas.

34:30.500 --> 34:32.433 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You have small money remitters.

34:32.433 --> 34:35.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And there's a
pawn shop, not the kind of
financier you would find on the

34:35.766 --> 34:37.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
actual Wall Street.

34:37.766 --> 34:42.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, hey, this is the South
Bronx, poorest congressional
district in America, where some

34:43.400 --> 34:45.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
40 percent of residents
live below the poverty line.

34:45.966 --> 34:50.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOE COLEMAN: The main service
provider on the street is
RiteCheck, where we have our

34:50.533 --> 34:52.633 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
financial service center.

34:52.633 --> 34:56.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Joe Coleman is
president of this chain of 14
stores in the South Bronx and

34:56.533 --> 34:58.566 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Harlem.

34:58.566 --> 35:02.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They will cash your checks,
pay your bills, transfer money
24 hours a day, 365 days a

35:04.900 --> 35:07.466 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
year.

35:07.466 --> 35:10.900 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Something like half these
customers are unbanked,
meaning they have no
bank account on purpose.

35:12.400 --> 35:14.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Jose Benitez is a
construction contractor.

35:14.366 --> 35:17.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOSE BENITEZ, Construction
Contractor (through translator):
Every time you go to a bank,

35:17.366 --> 35:18.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
there's a problem.

35:18.366 --> 35:19.866 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
You lose time.

35:19.866 --> 35:21.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: The bank takes too
long to cash checks, he says.

35:21.933 --> 35:24.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
WOMAN: Can you sign
there for me, please?

35:24.300 --> 35:26.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And, says
cashier Jackie Morel (ph):

35:26.966 --> 35:30.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JACKIE MOREL, Cashier:
The bank don't offer all
the services that we do.

35:30.466 --> 35:32.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We have prepaid cards.

35:32.366 --> 35:35.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
They pay their bills,
pay their rent.

35:35.000 --> 35:37.866 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's different things that
they can do in one place.

35:37.866 --> 35:42.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But the best
alternative is check cashers,
payday lenders, pawn shops?

35:44.333 --> 35:48.100 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Maybe you assume what I did,
that they prey on the poor.

35:48.100 --> 35:50.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Suzanne Martindale is
with Consumers Union.

35:50.166 --> 35:53.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SUZANNE MARTINDALE, Consumers
Union: Many of these products
really strip away what few

35:53.733 --> 35:56.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
assets consumers have.

35:56.400 --> 36:00.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If you're constantly paying
a fee to cash a check, you're
losing money on the deal,

36:00.733 --> 36:03.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
compared to if you
simply had an account and
were depositing checks.

36:03.733 --> 36:08.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Yet check cashing
alone nearly doubled to $60
billion from 2000 to 2010.

36:10.533 --> 36:12.566 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Why, wondered Lisa Servon?

36:12.566 --> 36:14.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA SERVON, University of
Pennsylvania: It didn't make
sense to me that people would

36:14.933 --> 36:19.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
be using a service like
this in increasing numbers
if it was so bad for them.

36:19.600 --> 36:24.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I had done work in low-income
neighborhoods for 20 years, and
I knew that people who don't

36:24.033 --> 36:26.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have very much money know
where every penny goes.

36:26.233 --> 36:29.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, that's when I scratched
my head and I realized there's
got to be more to the story.

36:29.966 --> 36:34.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: To find out,
Servon worked as a cashier at
this RiteCheck for four months

36:36.333 --> 36:38.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and then wrote a book,
"The Unbanking of America."

36:38.800 --> 36:43.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She returned to the window when
we visited, and was reminded
of what she'd learned: People

36:45.833 --> 36:48.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on the edge have no savings,
and often need access to every
cent they get can their hands

36:49.800 --> 36:51.800 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
on right away.

36:51.800 --> 36:55.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA SERVON: One of the things
that we do here is to take
money off of people's EBT

36:55.733 --> 36:57.233 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
cards.

36:57.233 --> 36:58.666 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's electronics benefit
transfer, what you get.

36:58.666 --> 37:00.133 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's kind of the equivalent
of welfare these days.

37:00.133 --> 37:01.600 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Right?

37:01.600 --> 37:04.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And we give you how much you
want from that, minus a $2 fee.

37:04.233 --> 37:07.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One day, a woman came
in and she wanted -- she
said had $10 on her card.

37:07.866 --> 37:11.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, I ran the transaction
and I gave her $8.

37:11.900 --> 37:15.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And after she left, I just
was scratching my head and
thinking, wow, she just paid me

37:15.766 --> 37:17.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
20 percent of what
was available to her.

37:17.866 --> 37:21.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Cashier Jackie
Morel, who taught Servon
the ropes here, explained.

37:21.500 --> 37:26.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA SERVON: Jackie says,
well, the ATMs don't give
you $8 or $13 or $28.

37:28.066 --> 37:32.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
They give you multiples
of $20, maybe $10, if
you're lucky, right?

37:32.466 --> 37:37.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, suddenly, something that
seems illogical makes sense,
because you realize that she

37:37.466 --> 37:39.466 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
needed that $8.

37:39.466 --> 37:42.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She needed every dollar that
she could get access to, and
it was worth it to her to spend

37:42.900 --> 37:44.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
$2 in order to get it.

37:44.966 --> 37:48.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Time and again, working at the
window, I was able to really
see those things, sometimes

37:48.133 --> 37:51.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ask questions, then
really see like, oh, this
is logical, actually.

37:51.500 --> 37:54.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
I would probably do
the same thing if I
was in that situation.

37:54.566 --> 37:56.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: Joe
Coleman goes further.

37:56.866 --> 38:01.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Firms like his, with regulated
maximum rates, were actually a
reform move by New York state

38:03.200 --> 38:07.466 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
back in 1944, when check
cashing was a truly free market.

38:07.466 --> 38:10.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOE COLEMAN: It was being
done in bars and restaurants.

38:10.233 --> 38:11.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It was the Wild West.

38:11.733 --> 38:14.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They could charge you 20,
30 percent to cash a check.

38:14.000 --> 38:19.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And while the fees
may seem high, says Servon,
they're completely transparent,

38:20.366 --> 38:22.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
unlike at banks, when you
rarely know what you're paying.

38:22.533 --> 38:26.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA SERVON: The signage that
spans the teller windows looks
exactly like what you would

38:26.833 --> 38:31.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
see at a fast-food restaurant
like McDonald's, and it tells
you that it costs 2.03 percent

38:33.766 --> 38:37.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of the face value of your check
to cash it, $1.50 to pay a
bill, $0.89 for a money order.

38:38.266 --> 38:40.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
All of that
information is there.

38:40.333 --> 38:43.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: Servon
also found that, for
those with no financial
cushion, cashing checks

38:43.666 --> 38:46.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
here can be cheaper
than at a bank.

38:46.200 --> 38:48.866 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA SERVON: If they
have deposited that check
in the bank, it would
take three or four days

38:48.866 --> 38:50.333 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to clear.

38:50.333 --> 38:52.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
When they come here, they
can use that cash right away.

38:52.966 --> 38:57.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they won't be subject to
the kind of mistiming at a bank
that could lead to an overdraft

38:57.366 --> 38:58.866 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
fee of $35.

38:58.866 --> 39:02.066 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Enough volume, and
even the smallest fees add up.

39:02.066 --> 39:07.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, RiteCheck caters
to folks that big banks
aren't much interested in.

39:08.500 --> 39:11.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Robert Flexer is a
RiteCheck devotee.

39:11.733 --> 39:14.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROBERT FLEXER, Uses
RiteCheck: The people are
so beautiful with you.

39:14.800 --> 39:17.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
They're so beautiful
and humble and lovable.

39:17.633 --> 39:21.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Jackie Morel
has worked behind the
counter for 14 years.

39:21.433 --> 39:23.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How many of the people who come
in here do you know personally?

39:23.933 --> 39:27.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JACKIE MOREL: Eighty-five
percent that comes
here every week.

39:27.933 --> 39:30.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Everybody know me in the
street and everything.

39:30.100 --> 39:31.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They bring me food.

39:31.566 --> 39:34.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
They bring me
presents for my kids.

39:34.000 --> 39:35.100 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They bring me everything.

39:35.100 --> 39:37.200 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

39:37.200 --> 39:41.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: OK, maybe there
are good reasons to use check
cashers, but surely not payday

39:42.533 --> 39:46.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
lenders, so common
in cash-strapped
communities these days.

39:46.500 --> 39:51.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Servon writes that there are
more payday lenders in the U.S.
than Starbucks and McDonald's

39:52.100 --> 39:53.300 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
combined.

39:53.300 --> 39:55.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And she herself
did a stint at one.

39:55.366 --> 39:59.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA SERVON: Where I worked
in California, they cost $15
per $100 borrowed, which comes

39:59.300 --> 40:02.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
out to an APR of 400
percent or 600 percent.

40:02.333 --> 40:06.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: That's APR,
annual percentage rate, because
it's 15 percent, $15 on 100.

40:06.533 --> 40:07.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
LISA SERVON: Yes.

40:07.533 --> 40:09.200 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
That's right.

40:09.200 --> 40:10.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
A lot of people end up
not being able to pay
the loan when it's due.

40:10.800 --> 40:12.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And this is where
the problem comes in.

40:12.466 --> 40:14.433 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Right?

40:14.433 --> 40:17.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If you can't pay that $100
loan back in two weeks, you
basically end up taking out that

40:17.300 --> 40:21.066 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
loan again and paying another
$15 for another two weeks.

40:21.066 --> 40:23.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
So, now you're
paying $30 on $100.

40:23.700 --> 40:25.833 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Right?

40:25.833 --> 40:28.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And if you roll it over five
or six times, you're paying
way more than you borrowed.

40:28.966 --> 40:30.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: But look,
says Joe Coleman:

40:30.633 --> 40:34.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JOE COLEMAN: There's
nowhere to go to get a
couple hundred dollars.

40:34.466 --> 40:39.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The payday industry has
evolved organically to solve a
short-term, immediate problem.

40:40.666 --> 40:42.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And I don't do the
product, by the way.

40:42.200 --> 40:44.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
In New York -- we don't do
payday lending in New York.

40:44.000 --> 40:46.633 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But you would?

40:46.633 --> 40:50.000 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOE COLEMAN: Yes, I would
if I could, because it's
a reasonable product, if
you use it responsibly

40:50.900 --> 40:52.866 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in the way it's designed.

40:52.866 --> 40:55.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Not surprisingly,
Suzanne Martindale of
Consumers Union disagrees.

40:55.233 --> 40:59.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SUZANNE MARTINDALE: The evidence
has been clear and damning
for many, many years that

40:59.933 --> 41:04.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the vast majority of people
that start to take out payday
loans end up in a cycle of

41:05.400 --> 41:07.433 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
debt.

41:07.433 --> 41:11.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Eighty percent of
payday loans are re-borrowed
within 14 days, and almost

41:11.333 --> 41:15.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
90 percent are re-borrowed
within 60 days.

41:15.000 --> 41:16.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
In fact, Servon says:

41:16.966 --> 41:19.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA SERVON: What's interesting
is that even my boss at the
payday lender said, payday

41:19.933 --> 41:23.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is a lousy product, but
we're filling a need that
nobody else will fill.

41:23.333 --> 41:27.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But aren't
the payday lenders taking
advantage of these people?

41:27.933 --> 41:31.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA SERVON: It's a very hard
question to answer, the question
really being, are payday

41:31.800 --> 41:36.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
loans helpful or harmful, or,
alternatively, is very expensive
credit better than no credit

41:37.400 --> 41:38.933 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
at all?

41:38.933 --> 41:41.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I would say that the jury
is still out on that question.

41:41.433 --> 41:46.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We talk about getting rid of
the lenders without recognizing
that the demand is still there.

41:48.400 --> 41:52.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the demand is still there
because we have had declining
wages since the '70s,.

41:54.633 --> 41:57.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Income volatility has doubled
over the past 30 years, so
people have much less ability

41:57.600 --> 42:00.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to predict how much money
is coming into their
household from week to week.

42:00.933 --> 42:05.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And the less
predictable the income, says
Joe Coleman, the greater the

42:05.200 --> 42:08.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
need for check cashing,
for payday lending even.

42:08.666 --> 42:13.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOE COLEMAN: Voltaire said
of the supreme being that,
if he didn't exist, we'd have

42:13.133 --> 42:14.366 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to invent him.

42:14.366 --> 42:16.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And the same can be
said for our industry.

42:16.033 --> 42:18.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
If we didn't exist, you
would have to invent us.

42:18.466 --> 42:20.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
People need the service.

42:20.566 --> 42:25.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: For the
"PBS NewsHour," this is
economics correspondent
Paul Solman reporting

42:26.166 --> 42:30.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
from the South Bronx.

42:30.500 --> 42:35.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Now to issues
of policing, race and the
law, issues in the forefront

42:42.033 --> 42:43.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of the news once again.

42:43.933 --> 42:45.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
John Yang has our look.

42:45.933 --> 42:48.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A warning: This story includes
images of violence that
viewers may find disturbing.

42:48.366 --> 42:50.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JERONIMO YANEZ, St. Anthony
Police Department: Hello, sir.

42:50.800 --> 42:55.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: This week, the public
got to see the dash-cam video
of last July's fatal police

42:57.300 --> 43:01.133 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
shooting of Philando Castile
outside St. Paul, Minnesota.

43:01.133 --> 43:06.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Jurors had watched it several
times before acquitting
officer Jeronimo Yanez.

43:07.566 --> 43:10.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
A conversation about a broken
taillight quickly turned tense.

43:10.433 --> 43:12.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PHILANDO CASTILE, Killed by
Police Officer: Sir, I have to
tell you, I do have a firearm

43:12.800 --> 43:13.800 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
on me.

43:13.800 --> 43:14.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JERONIMO YANEZ: OK.

43:14.800 --> 43:15.800 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
OK.

43:15.800 --> 43:16.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Don't reach for it then.

43:16.800 --> 43:18.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Don't pull it out.

43:18.033 --> 43:19.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
PHILANDO CASTILE: I'm
not pulling it out.

43:19.266 --> 43:20.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JERONIMO YANEZ:
Don't pull it out.

43:20.533 --> 43:22.633 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(GUNSHOTS)

43:22.633 --> 43:25.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Prosecutors said
Castile, who had a permit for
the gun, was reaching for his

43:25.466 --> 43:27.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
driver's license.

43:27.033 --> 43:30.066 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Yanez said he thought he
was reaching for his gun.

43:30.066 --> 43:33.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The day he was acquitted,
Yanez was fired.

43:33.433 --> 43:38.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Since 2005, 82 U.S. law
enforcement officers
have been charged with
murder or manslaughter

43:40.333 --> 43:44.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for on-duty shootings,
according to Bowling Green State
University criminologist Philip

43:45.333 --> 43:46.733 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Stinson.

43:46.733 --> 43:51.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So far, 29 have been convicted,
five of them for murder.

43:53.366 --> 43:56.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Yesterday, a jury found
former Milwaukee police
officer Dominique
Heaggan-Brown not guilty

43:58.033 --> 44:01.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
of reckless homicide
for shooting Sylville
Smith last August.

44:01.700 --> 44:06.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
In court, Smith's family
shouted and cursed.

44:06.166 --> 44:11.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Body-camera video
caught Heaggan-Brown's
brief chase of Smith.

44:13.233 --> 44:16.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Heaggan-Brown's first shot
came as Smith appeared to
throw a gun over a fence.

44:16.600 --> 44:18.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
A second shot hit
Smith in the chest.

44:18.600 --> 44:21.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DOMINIQUE HEAGGAN-BROWN,
Milwaukee Police
Department: Stop reaching!

44:21.666 --> 44:22.666 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Stop -- move!

44:22.666 --> 44:23.933 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Move!

44:23.933 --> 44:26.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JOHN YANG: He said he
acted in self-defense.

44:26.466 --> 44:30.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
The shooting sparked
two nights of riots.

44:30.400 --> 44:35.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And police use of deadly
force is under scrutiny
again in Seattle, where
officers in shot and

44:37.766 --> 44:40.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
killed Charleena Lyles,
a 30-year-old pregnant
woman who had called
police to report a burglary

44:41.766 --> 44:43.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
at her apartment Sunday.

44:43.800 --> 44:48.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She had two kitchen knives
and, her family said,
mental health problems.

44:50.633 --> 44:54.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
As protesters took to the
streets, Seattle police, who
are investigating the incident,

44:55.600 --> 44:58.266 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
acknowledged the officers
had less lethal options.

44:58.266 --> 45:03.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, why do so many -- few -- so
few trials of police officers
charged in on-duty shootings

45:05.433 --> 45:07.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
end in convictions?

45:07.400 --> 45:12.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
To explore that question,
we're joined by two guests,
first, on Skype, David Klinger.

45:14.233 --> 45:16.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's a criminologist at the
University of Missouri-Saint
Louis and a former Los Angeles

45:16.766 --> 45:18.800 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
police officer.

45:18.800 --> 45:23.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And here in the studio, Brittany
Packnett, a co-founder of
Campaign Zero, which is pressing

45:23.900 --> 45:25.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
for police reform.

45:25.900 --> 45:29.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She served on President Barack
Obama's Police Reform Task
Force and is one of a number of

45:30.933 --> 45:32.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
leaders in the Black
Lives Matter movement.

45:32.366 --> 45:33.866 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Thank you both for joining us.

45:33.866 --> 45:36.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I want to ask you first, the
two of you the same question.

45:36.533 --> 45:38.866 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Brittany, let me start with you.

45:38.866 --> 45:43.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Why does it -- is it seemingly
so few of these police trials,
police shooting trials end

45:44.900 --> 45:46.933 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in convictions?

45:46.933 --> 45:48.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BRITTANY PACKNETT, Co-Founder,
Campaign Zero: It's because
this is more than an individual

45:48.000 --> 45:49.000 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
issue.

45:49.000 --> 45:51.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's a systematic issue.

45:51.033 --> 45:54.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So often we hear the
conversation that it's
about bad apples and
bad actors, but, at the

45:54.566 --> 45:59.566 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
end of the day, if this
were just about individuals,
we wouldn't see less than
1 percent of convictions

46:00.366 --> 46:02.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in all police shootings.

46:02.400 --> 46:06.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Of the 1,155 people who were
killed by police in 2016, there
were only 13 charges brought,

46:08.600 --> 46:10.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and so far we have
seen no convictions.

46:10.666 --> 46:14.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
At the end of the day, this
is a systematic issue that we
have to look at, both from a

46:14.533 --> 46:16.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
cultural perspective
and a policy one.

46:16.600 --> 46:19.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN YANG: David
Klinger, what's you take?

46:19.000 --> 46:20.866 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID KLINGER, Professor,
University of Missouri-Saint
Louis: Well, there's
really two issues.

46:20.866 --> 46:23.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
One is the number of
charges that are levied.

46:23.166 --> 46:27.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then number two is the
conviction rate for those
where charges have been brought

46:27.700 --> 46:29.766 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
forth.

46:29.766 --> 46:33.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And in terms of why so
few charges are brought
forth, I think, if you
take an honest look

46:33.566 --> 46:38.566 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
at the vast, vast majority
of officer-involved
shootings, there is no
criminal element whatsoever.

46:40.900 --> 46:44.000 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For those that do lead to
criminal charges, sometimes,
there is overcharge,
and then sometimes

46:46.000 --> 46:50.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
there are situations where I
and friends of mine, others
in this profession, we scratch

46:53.166 --> 46:56.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
our heads and don't understand
how the acquittal came about.

46:56.933 --> 47:01.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But we always have to trust
in the jury, and that's
where we rest with this.

47:03.066 --> 47:04.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JOHN YANG: David,
let my stay with you.

47:04.700 --> 47:09.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Are the laws written
in a way that makes it
tougher for convictions?

47:11.066 --> 47:15.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID KLINGER: Well, I think one
of the things that people have
to understand is that there's

47:15.400 --> 47:20.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
basically a federal standard
that was laid down in Graham
vs. Connor, which is a 1989

47:22.366 --> 47:26.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
U.S. Supreme Court ruling that
says you have to look at it
through the eyes of a reasonable

47:26.066 --> 47:28.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
officer on the scene.

47:28.166 --> 47:32.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so what has happened over
the years is that most states,
that I'm aware of at least,

47:32.033 --> 47:37.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they basically incorporate
this standard of an objectively
reasonable officer on the scene.

47:39.066 --> 47:43.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then what happens is, we
have a situation where defense
attorneys explain to the jury

47:45.200 --> 47:47.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
what a reasonable officer
at the scene could have
or should have done.

47:47.533 --> 47:51.266 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And then the jury has to look
at it that way typically.

47:51.266 --> 47:56.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, there's always differences
across the 50 states in terms
of their justifiable homicide

47:57.633 --> 47:59.633 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
statute.

47:59.633 --> 48:03.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I think that's the core
understanding across the country
about how it is that police

48:04.500 --> 48:06.533 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
officers are to be judged.

48:06.533 --> 48:10.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so, consequently, when you
have jurors who are novices
getting educated, a good defense

48:12.333 --> 48:15.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
attorney makes an argument, and
the jury says, oh, that make
sense, I understand that that

48:15.700 --> 48:20.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
officer could have been fearful
or could have perceived that
his or her life was in jeopardy,

48:22.566 --> 48:25.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and an acquittal is forthcoming,
and, as I indicated, sometimes
clearly so, and, other

48:27.600 --> 48:30.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
times, it leaves many of us
who are in the profession
scratching our head, because we

48:30.166 --> 48:32.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
know there's bad shootings
and we know there's bad cops.

48:32.433 --> 48:36.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Brittany, you
have heard the explanation
of the law from David.

48:36.566 --> 48:38.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What's your response?

48:38.033 --> 48:39.233 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What's your take on this?

48:39.233 --> 48:41.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
BRITTANY PACKNETT: I
would say it's twofold.

48:41.300 --> 48:44.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One is that we actually do
have to look at the letter of
the law and the ways in which

48:44.200 --> 48:45.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
it's insufficient.

48:45.700 --> 48:48.366 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
At Campaign Zero, we did a
report on the use of force.

48:48.366 --> 48:52.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We found the research that
there are eight policies that
both police departments and

48:52.533 --> 48:57.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
state legislatures can take
on that will demonstrably
diminish the possibility
of police violence.

48:59.333 --> 49:02.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Very few police departments
engage in five of --
even five of those.

49:02.666 --> 49:06.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And if it's not legal, then
it's not punishable in the court
system, so that's certainly an

49:06.333 --> 49:07.600 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
area in which we need to look.

49:07.600 --> 49:09.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And we need to make
those laws stronger.

49:09.700 --> 49:12.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The other point, though, that
we have to not be afraid the
look at is the issue of race.

49:12.866 --> 49:16.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
At the end of the day, black
people in this country are
killed at a rate of three times

49:16.800 --> 49:18.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
higher than other
folks by police.

49:18.966 --> 49:23.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And if blackness is seen as the
only weapon that you are armed
with, it is still considered

49:23.000 --> 49:25.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
lethal in this country.

49:25.033 --> 49:27.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We continue to find that in
the number of charges and
convictions that are brought.

49:27.466 --> 49:31.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
We continue to find
that in places like
Seattle with Charleena
Myles -- Lyles, rather.

49:31.366 --> 49:34.266 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, at the end of the day,
my blackness is not a weapon.

49:34.266 --> 49:36.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's just my skin.

49:36.300 --> 49:39.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Until we handle our issue of
racism in this country, we're
not going to see an issue -- an

49:39.233 --> 49:41.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
end to this issue.

49:41.266 --> 49:45.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: A lot of cities
try to address that, Brittany,
very diversifying the police

49:46.666 --> 49:49.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
force, by getting more diverse
faces on the police force.

49:49.433 --> 49:50.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Is that an answer?

49:50.866 --> 49:52.466 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BRITTANY PACKNETT: I certainly
think that's part of it.

49:52.466 --> 49:54.766 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But it's not a single issue.

49:54.766 --> 49:57.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And so we can't have a
single answer, right?

49:57.200 --> 50:01.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have to look at issues of
inherent bias, which, quite
frankly, especially issues of

50:01.266 --> 50:05.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
anti-blackness, are not just
about white people or whether
or not you're a person of color.

50:05.666 --> 50:10.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We also have to look at issues
of training, support, again,
use of force policies, making

50:10.566 --> 50:15.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
sure that, as a citizen, I can
walk around and feel safe in
my community by someone who

50:16.733 --> 50:18.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
has sworn an oath to
serve and protect me.

50:18.166 --> 50:20.200 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN YANG: David, Brittany
mentioned training.

50:20.200 --> 50:24.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In the Seattle case we just
heard in that tape piece,
the police acknowledged those

50:24.366 --> 50:28.066 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
offers had non-lethal
options that they didn't use.

50:28.066 --> 50:31.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
How much is this
a training issue?

50:31.233 --> 50:34.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
DAVID KLINGER: I think
a big piece of it.

50:34.266 --> 50:39.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And I would argue that
the race issue is one
that gets overplayed.

50:40.166 --> 50:42.300 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And what I mean by that is this.

50:42.300 --> 50:46.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If we look at shootings that
could have been prevented, and
it goes back the training and

50:47.866 --> 50:51.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
tactics, we can pretty
much eliminate, in my
opinion, the race piece.

50:53.900 --> 50:57.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, for example, here in Saint
Louis, myself and Rick Rosenfeld
and two other colleagues

50:57.266 --> 51:02.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
were able to look at the spatial
patterns of officer-involved
shootings in the city

51:03.200 --> 51:05.200 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of Saint Louis.

51:05.200 --> 51:08.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And at first, it clearly
looks as if race plays a role,
but once you control for the

51:08.700 --> 51:11.866 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
levels of crime across
neighborhoods, that drops out.

51:11.866 --> 51:16.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so that's one example of
why I'm not going to get on to
the issue of race being the key.

51:18.933 --> 51:23.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I really think it has to deal
with the tactical performance
of police officers across the

51:25.866 --> 51:27.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
board dealing with
whites, blacks, Hispanics,
males, females, where
they don't use sound

51:27.633 --> 51:32.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
tactics that then lead
to the shootings that we
scratch our heads over.

51:34.466 --> 51:36.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the issue with Seattle,
when they say they had
non-lethal options, that doesn't

51:36.733 --> 51:41.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
necessarily mean they
had non-lethal options
to be employed in that
situation, but rather

51:41.233 --> 51:43.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
that they had non-lethal
options with them.

51:43.500 --> 51:46.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And so I'm not quite
sure what that means.

51:46.266 --> 51:50.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Seattle situation may well
have been one of those where
they could have employed a

51:50.000 --> 51:53.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
non-lethal option and they
didn't, or it may simply mean
that they had them with them.

51:53.966 --> 51:56.300 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so we have to wait and
see what the details show.

51:56.300 --> 51:59.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JOHN YANG: Brittany,
you mentioned both
training and race.

51:59.266 --> 52:01.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
How do you balance
those two issues?

52:01.633 --> 52:04.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
BRITTANY PACKNETT: I
don't think that it's an
either/or proposition.

52:04.300 --> 52:08.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I certainly agree that there are
tactical issues, as Professor
Klinger has already said.

52:08.666 --> 52:12.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But if race weren't an issue,
we wouldn't be being killed
at three times the rate of

52:12.333 --> 52:14.433 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
others.

52:14.433 --> 52:17.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
We did this research at
mapping police violence,
which is another project
of Campaign Zero.

52:17.166 --> 52:22.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And from looking over three
years of data for community
violence across the 60 largest

52:24.600 --> 52:26.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
police departments in
the country and comparing
that to rates of police
violence, there is

52:26.633 --> 52:30.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
absolutely no correlation
between community violence
and police violence.

52:30.100 --> 52:33.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In fact, in places like Virginia
Beach, where there is a very
low incidence of community

52:33.866 --> 52:38.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
violence, there is a very high
incidence of police violence,
and everyone that Virginia

52:39.733 --> 52:41.333 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Beach killed in 2015 was black.

52:41.333 --> 52:46.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, I refuse to ignore the
race question in this issue.

52:47.900 --> 52:51.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And if we do ignore
race in this issue, then
we do so at our peril.

52:51.000 --> 52:54.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Brittany Packnett,
David Klinger, thank
you both for joining us.

52:54.366 --> 52:57.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Sadly, I think this is an issue
we will be talking about again.

52:57.900 --> 53:02.900 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But thank you for joining us.

53:06.466 --> 53:11.466 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
BRITTANY PACKNETT: Thank you.

